{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476662"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:50:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:50:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13806"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13806"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.09,0.16,0.59,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48907"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6423"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13806"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33907"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2228"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"8118"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13359"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48907"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with her parents due to a three-day history of fever, cough, and difficulty breathing. She has no significant medical history and is up to date with immunisations. She does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears unwell with increased work of breathing. Her pulse rate is 130/min, respiratory rate 40/min, temperature 38.5\u00b0C, and oxygen saturation 94% on room air. Chest auscultation reveals good air entry bilaterally with no added sounds. A chest X-ray is ordered (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Viral bronchiolitis","Chest mass","Atypical pneumonia","Lobar pneumonia","Pleural effusion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray shows a rounded opacity in the right upper lobe, consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Elobar pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the correct diagnosis despite the absence of auscultatory findings on examination. In children, lobar pneumonia often has a rounded appearance on chest X-ray, which can be mistaken for a mass lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EViral bronchiolitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects infants under 12 months and presents with wheeze and crackles on auscultation. The chest X-ray would show hyperinflation rather than a focal opacity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Echest mass\u003C/strong\u003E such as a tumour would typically present with a longer history of symptoms and might be associated with other systemic symptoms like weight loss or night sweats. While it can appear as a rounded opacity on chest X-ray, the acute presentation and associated fever in this case make lobar pneumonia more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtypical pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E, often caused by organisms like \u003Cem\u003EMycoplasma pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E, typically presents with a more gradual onset and less severe symptoms. The chest X-ray in atypical pneumonia often shows a diffuse, interstitial pattern rather than a focal, lobar consolidation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epleural effusion\u003C/strong\u003E would typically show as a homogeneous opacity that obscures the costophrenic angle and has a meniscus sign on an erect chest X-ray, rather than a rounded opacity within the lung field.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case illustrates that a clear chest on auscultation with increased work of breathing should prompt further investigation with a chest X-ray, as significant pathology such as lobar pneumonia can be present despite the absence of auscultatory findings.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lobar pneumonia in children can present with a clear chest on auscultation but increased work of breathing.","A chest X-ray should be ordered if there is a clear chest on auscultation but increased work of breathing.","Lobar pneumonia often has a rounded appearance on chest X-ray in children."],"references":["Community-acquired pneumonia in children: Clinical features and diagnosis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024; cited 2024 Jun 28. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/community-acquired-pneumonia-in-children-clinical-features-and-diagnosis","Stuckey-Schrock K, Hayes BL, George CM. Community-acquired pneumonia in children. Am Fam Physician. 2012 Oct 1;86(7):661-7. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2012/1001/p661.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33907"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13806"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20749"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20749"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EKiEhlRAk8pMBKUpB01cllOEf1G2yt.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/EKiEhlRAk8pMBKUpB01cllOEf1G2yt.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":631,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33907","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33907"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T14:09:34